## Plan (round 4)

**Approach:** Refactor `internal/cli/init.go` into a plan -> apply pipeline over an ordered Action list, preserving EVERY observable behavior (write-then-error ordering, --force silence on refspecs, the five legacy strings, refspec idempotency) and adding `--dry-run` + a summary line, with `r.stdin` threaded unused. Round-4 adopts a READ-ONLY-AWARE action signature so dry-run never mutates and never needs separate preview metadata, fixing the round-3 --force output regression and the dry-run count gaps in one model.

UNIFIED ACTION MODEL:
- `run func(force, dryRun bool) ([]actionLine, error)`. In dryRun the action is READ-ONLY (os.Stat / remoteExists only) and returns PREVIEW lines reflecting the ACTUAL outcome; otherwise it performs the effect and returns result lines. apply() calls run(force, dryRun) for EVERY action and is the SOLE print + tally site.
- `type actionLine struct { status actionStatus; text string }`.
- `type actionStatus string` consts: `statusCreated`, `statusSkipped`, `statusConfigured`, `statusAlreadyConfigured`, plus uncounted sentinel `statusNote`. Errors flow through Go `error`.
- `type initAction struct { describe string; run func(force, dryRun bool) ([]actionLine, error) }`.

Behavior to preserve (verified init.go:43-74): `run()` writes the scaffold (prints `created`) BEFORE any remote-existence check, so `init --remote <bad>` and `init --force --remote <bad>` write then error. Legacy `--force` is SILENT on every refspec outcome EXCEPT (remoteChanged && absent) which errors (init.go:66-71 returns nil after the explicit-missing check; it never prints a skip note and never configures).

plan(ctx, root, force, remote, remoteChanged) ([]initAction, error): read-only DERIVATION only — `.etude`-is-a-file guard (init.go:81), workflow self-check (`workflow.Default()` -> `YAML()` -> round-trip ParseYAML, init.go:86-95), rubric derivation (init.go:102-107). These two guards legitimately error PRE-APPLY even under --dry-run (pure validation, no writes) — explicitly acceptable. plan() builds, deterministically: workflow.yaml write action, one write action per rubric placeholder, then EXACTLY ONE refspec-phase action. plan() NEVER calls remoteExists and NEVER returns remoteNotFoundErr.

Write action run(force, dryRun):
- dryRun: os.Stat(path) ONLY (read-only). Exists && !force -> return `{statusSkipped, "skipped <path>"}` previewed as a `plan: skip <path>` line; else -> `{statusCreated, "plan: create <path>"}`. (Use the SHARED string consts; see below.) No MkdirAll, no WriteFile.
- normal: call writeScaffoldFile(path, content, force) -> returns (actionStatus, error); wrap into one actionLine with the verbatim `created %s` / `skipped %s` text.

Refspec phase = ONE action (so the skip note prints at most once). run(force, dryRun):
- FORCE GATE FIRST (fixes blocker 1): if `force`, the phase produces ZERO output lines in ALL cases except the explicit-missing error. Specifically: if remoteChanged && !remoteExists -> return error remoteNotFoundErr(remote) (writes already happened -> write-then-error preserved); otherwise (force) return NO lines (no skip-note, no configure) in BOTH normal and dryRun. This matches legacy --force silence and gives dry-run --force a "to configure" count of 0 (directive D).
- NON-FORCE:
  - dryRun: remoteExists? present -> `{statusConfigured x2}` preview lines `plan: configure refspecs on <remote>` counted as 2 to-configure (so dry-run agrees with a real run); absent -> ONE `{statusNote, "remote <remote> not found -> would skip refspec configuration"}`, uncounted; NEVER errors on a missing remote (even when remoteChanged — dry-run is report-only).
  - normal: remote absent + remoteChanged -> return error remoteNotFoundErr; remote absent + !remoteChanged -> ONE `{statusNote, "remote %s not found, skipping refspec configuration"}` (verbatim, uncounted); remote present -> addRefspecIfAbsent for fetch then push -> TWO actionLines each `{status, "configured %s = %s" | "already configured %s = %s"}`.

apply(ctx, w, actions, force, dryRun) error — the SOLE fmt.Fprintf + tally site:
- for each action call run(force, dryRun). On error, return it immediately (in a normal run the earlier write actions already printed -> realizes write-then-error). Else print each line.text and tally each line.status.
- After all actions, print the summary: normal `init: %d created, %d skipped, %d configured`; dry-run `dry-run: %d to create, %d to skip, %d to configure`.

Status -> bucket mapping (pinned, identical normal & dry-run):
- created  <- statusCreated
- skipped  <- statusSkipped
- configured <- statusConfigured + statusAlreadyConfigured (both)
- statusNote UNCOUNTED.

run() collapses to: `validateRemoteName(remote)` (syntactic, pre-everything, unchanged — errors even under --dry-run) -> `repoRoot(ctx)` -> `plan(...)` -> `apply(..., force, dryRun)`.

Helper change (retained): writeScaffoldFile + addRefspecIfAbsent RETURN `(actionStatus, error)` and REMOVE internal fmt.Fprintf; apply() is the one print site. (For dryRun the write action does NOT call writeScaffoldFile at all — it does its own os.Stat preview — so writeScaffoldFile never writes during dry-run.)

Shared string consts (optional-but-doing-it, prevents drift): hoist the five legacy strings into package consts used by BOTH apply normal output and dry-run preview where applicable: `created %s`, `skipped %s`, `configured %s = %s`, `already configured %s = %s`, `remote %s not found, skipping refspec configuration`. These stay BYTE-IDENTICAL.

r.stdin: add `stdin io.Reader` to initRunner (init.go:38), wire `stdin: cmd.InOrStdin()` in newInitCommand. Unused this bead.

Verbatim-string discipline (pinned):
- `--dry-run` BoolVar help: "preview the planned actions without writing files or modifying git config".
- dry-run per-action lines: `plan: create <path>`, `plan: skip <path>`, `plan: configure refspecs on <remote>`; absent-remote uses the would-skip note text above.
- Normal summary: `init: %d created, %d skipped, %d configured`.
- Dry-run summary: `dry-run: %d to create, %d to skip, %d to configure`.

Existing-test compatibility (verified): init_test.go asserts via strings.Contains(stdout, ...) (substrings/counts), NOT full-buffer equality -> the trailing summary line does NOT break the 14 existing tests; they stay as-is.

